WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=LOCAL:00:00:00.000,MPEGTS:144533

1
00:00:02.102 --> 00:00:03.203
In the previous lesson,

2
00:00:03.203 --> 00:00:06.206
we built an agent
that can reason over a single document

3
00:00:06.406 --> 00:00:09.576
and answer complex questions over it,
while maintaining memory.

4
00:00:10.343 --> 00:00:12.979
In this lesson,
you will learn how to extend that agent

5
00:00:12.979 --> 00:00:16.649
to handle multiple documents
and increasing degrees of complexity.

6
00:00:17.117 --> 00:00:19.953
Let's get coding.

7
00:00:19.953 --> 00:00:22.322
We'll start with a three document
use case,

8
00:00:22.322 --> 00:00:25.291
and then we'll expand to an 11 document
use case.

9
00:00:25.825 --> 00:00:28.728
We'll set up our OpenAI key
as well as import

10
00:00:28.728 --> 00:00:31.731
nest asyncio.

11
00:00:35.335 --> 00:00:37.137
And then the first task is to set up

12
00:00:37.137 --> 00:00:40.140
our function
calling agent over three papers.

13
00:00:40.173 --> 00:00:44.677
So we do this by combining
the vector summary tools for each document

14
00:00:44.677 --> 00:00:45.879
into a list

15
00:00:45.879 --> 00:00:49.816
and passing it to the agent so that
the agent actually has six tools in total.

16
00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:54.120
So we'll download
three papers from Eichler 2024,

17
00:00:54.754 --> 00:00:56.823
this includes Meta GPT from last time,

18
00:00:56.823 --> 00:00:59.893
but this also includes longlora
as well as selfrag.

19
00:01:00.660 --> 00:01:03.496
Next,
we'll convert each paper into a tool.

20
00:01:06.066 --> 00:01:09.135
So if you remember from lesson three
we have a helper

21
00:01:09.135 --> 00:01:13.606
function called Gap Doc Tools,
which automatically builds both a vector

22
00:01:13.606 --> 00:01:17.444
index tool as well
summary index tool over a given paper.

23
00:01:17.911 --> 00:01:20.380
And so the vector tool performs
vector search.

24
00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:23.883
And the summary tool performs
summarization over the entire document.

25
00:01:25.051 --> 00:01:28.388
So for each paper, we get back
both the vector tool and summary tool,

26
00:01:28.655 --> 00:01:31.724
and we put it into this overall
dictionary, mapping each paper

27
00:01:31.724 --> 00:01:34.727
name to the vector tool and summary tool.

28
00:01:37.730 --> 00:01:39.866
Next we'll simply get these tools

29
00:01:39.866 --> 00:01:42.869
in a flat list.

30
00:01:45.839 --> 00:01:46.473
We'll define

31
00:01:46.473 --> 00:01:49.909
3.5 turbo from OpenAI
as our LLM of choice.

32
00:01:52.045 --> 00:01:54.481
If we quickly take a look
at the number of tools

33
00:01:54.481 --> 00:01:56.216
that are going to be passed to the agent,

34
00:01:56.216 --> 00:01:57.851
we'll see that the number is six.

35
00:01:57.851 --> 00:02:01.254
That's because we have three papers,
and we have two tools for each paper

36
00:02:01.588 --> 00:02:02.755
a factory and a summary tool.

37
00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:05.758
The next step is to construct

38
00:02:05.758 --> 00:02:08.761
our overall agent worker.

39
00:02:10.363 --> 00:02:11.731
And this agent worker

40
00:02:11.731 --> 00:02:15.235
includes the six tools
as well as the LLM that we pass out.

41
00:02:17.403 --> 00:02:19.072
And now we're able to ask questions

42
00:02:19.072 --> 00:02:22.075
across these three documents
or within a single document.

43
00:02:22.442 --> 00:02:25.445
For now, let's quickly
ask a question about Longlora.

44
00:02:25.879 --> 00:02:27.313
"Tell me about the eval data set.

45
00:02:27.313 --> 00:02:30.316
Use longlora,
and then tell me about the eval results."

46
00:02:42.061 --> 00:02:43.296
We get back the answer

47
00:02:43.296 --> 00:02:46.833
that the one of the eval data sets use
is a feature 19 test split.

48
00:02:47.767 --> 00:02:51.171
And that we're able to look at the eval
results for our long haul models.

49
00:02:51.704 --> 00:02:54.174
The next question we can ask
is "give me a summary of

50
00:02:54.174 --> 00:02:57.177
both selfrag and Longlora."

51
00:02:57.177 --> 00:03:00.747
So this will actually allow us
to do summarization across two papers.

52
00:03:01.447 --> 00:03:03.783
So first we call the summary tool

53
00:03:03.783 --> 00:03:06.786
for self rag with the input of its name

54
00:03:07.086 --> 00:03:10.757
variable to get back the output
describing what the paper is about.

55
00:03:12.959 --> 00:03:13.493
We see that

56
00:03:13.493 --> 00:03:17.096
the agent then calls a longLora
summary tool with the input longlora,

57
00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:20.633
and then we get back
an overall summary of longlora.

58
00:03:22.302 --> 00:03:24.671
The final response
is that we're able to get back

59
00:03:24.671 --> 00:03:27.874
both a summary of selfrag,
as well as longora.

60
00:03:29.609 --> 00:03:31.945
If you want to try out
some queries on your own,

61
00:03:31.945 --> 00:03:36.015
you can try out any combination
of these two papers or even three papers

62
00:03:36.349 --> 00:03:39.352
and ask for both summaries
as well as specific information

63
00:03:39.519 --> 00:03:43.256
within the papers to see whether or not
the agent is able to reason

64
00:03:43.256 --> 00:03:46.259
about the summary
and vector tools for each document.

65
00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:50.730
Now, let's expand into a more advanced use
case.

66
00:03:51.464 --> 00:03:54.467
Here it will actually have
11 Eichler papers,

67
00:03:54.567 --> 00:03:58.771
and so we'll download
11 research papers from Eichler 2024.

68
00:04:02.141 --> 00:04:04.010
This includes papers like

69
00:04:04.010 --> 00:04:07.780
Meta GPT,
LongLora, LoftQ, Swebench, SelfRag,

70
00:04:08.014 --> 00:04:11.017
as well as a few others.

71
00:04:11.551 --> 00:04:13.353
Similar to the previous section,

72
00:04:13.353 --> 00:04:16.589
we will now build a dictionary mapping

73
00:04:16.589 --> 00:04:19.592
each paper to its vector and summary tool.

74
00:04:20.093 --> 00:04:22.195
This section can also take
a little bit of time,

75
00:04:22.195 --> 00:04:25.298
since we need to process, index and embed

76
00:04:25.832 --> 00:04:28.801
11 documents.

77
00:04:29.869 --> 00:04:30.837
Now let's collapse

78
00:04:30.837 --> 00:04:33.840
these tools into a flat list.

79
00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:36.442
This is the point
at which we need a slightly

80
00:04:36.442 --> 00:04:39.445
more advanced
agent and tool architecture.

81
00:04:39.445 --> 00:04:42.215
The issue is that let's say
we try to index

82
00:04:42.215 --> 00:04:45.485
all 11 papers,
which now includes 20 tools.

83
00:04:46.152 --> 00:04:50.223
Or let's say we try to index 100 papers
or 1000 papers or more.

84
00:04:51.090 --> 00:04:54.661
Even though LLM context
windows are getting longer, stuffing

85
00:04:54.661 --> 00:04:58.765
too many tool selections into the LLM
prompt leads to the following issues:

86
00:04:59.432 --> 00:05:02.135
One is,
the tools may not all fit in the prompt,

87
00:05:02.135 --> 00:05:03.636
especially if your number of documents

88
00:05:03.636 --> 00:05:07.340
are big and you're modeling each document
as a separate tool or a set of tools.

89
00:05:07.707 --> 00:05:11.210
Costs and latency will spike
because you're increasing the number

90
00:05:11.210 --> 00:05:15.281
of tokens in your prompt, and also
the outline can actually get confused.

91
00:05:15.782 --> 00:05:16.949
The LLM may fail

92
00:05:16.949 --> 00:05:20.219
to pick the right tool
when the number of choices is too large.

93
00:05:20.787 --> 00:05:25.787
A solution here is that when the user asks
a query, we actually perform Retrieval

94
00:05:26.392 --> 00:05:29.696
Augmentation,
but not on the level of text, but actually

95
00:05:29.696 --> 00:05:31.497
on the level of tools.

96
00:05:31.497 --> 00:05:34.767
We first retrieve a small set
of relevant tools, and then feed

97
00:05:34.767 --> 00:05:38.638
the relevant tools to the agent
reasoning prompt instead of all the tools.

98
00:05:39.339 --> 00:05:43.109
This retrieval process is similar to
the retrieval process used in RAG.

99
00:05:43.643 --> 00:05:46.546
At its simplest,
it can just be top k vector search.

100
00:05:46.546 --> 00:05:49.282
But of course you can add all the advanced
retrieval techniques

101
00:05:49.282 --> 00:05:52.151
you want to filter out
the relevant set of results.

102
00:05:52.151 --> 00:05:55.054
Our agents
let you plug in a tool retriever

103
00:05:55.054 --> 00:05:57.690
that allows you to accomplish exactly
this.

104
00:05:57.690 --> 00:05:59.859
So let's show
you how to actually get this done.

105
00:06:00.827 --> 00:06:03.229
First, we'll want to index the tools.

106
00:06:03.229 --> 00:06:06.632
LlamaIndex already has extensive
indexing capabilities over

107
00:06:06.632 --> 00:06:08.401
general text documents.

108
00:06:08.401 --> 00:06:12.205
But since these tools are actually
Python objects, we need a way to convert

109
00:06:12.205 --> 00:06:15.208
and serialize these objects
to a string representation and back.

110
00:06:15.241 --> 00:06:18.511
This is solved through the object
index abstraction in LlamaIndex.

111
00:06:21.848 --> 00:06:25.551
So we'll define an object
index and retriever over these tools.

112
00:06:25.651 --> 00:06:27.153
We see that we import a vector

113
00:06:27.153 --> 00:06:30.323
store index, which is our standard interface
for indexing text.

114
00:06:30.923 --> 00:06:33.793
But then we wrap this with object index.

115
00:06:33.793 --> 00:06:35.428
And to construct an object index,

116
00:06:35.428 --> 00:06:38.865
we see
we directly plug in these Python tools

117
00:06:38.865 --> 00:06:41.868
as input into the index.

118
00:06:42.335 --> 00:06:43.469
You can retrieve from

119
00:06:43.469 --> 00:06:46.472
an object
index through an object retriever.

120
00:06:46.806 --> 00:06:49.976
This will call the underlying retriever
or from the index, and return

121
00:06:49.976 --> 00:06:51.377
the output directly as objects.

122
00:06:52.879 --> 00:06:55.882
In this case, it will be tools.

123
00:06:58.951 --> 00:07:00.286
Now that we've defined the object

124
00:07:00.286 --> 00:07:03.289
retriever,
let's walk through a very simple example.

125
00:07:04.090 --> 00:07:04.857
Let's ask:

126
00:07:04.857 --> 00:07:09.362
"Tell me about the eval data set
used a Meta GPT and also a Swebench."

127
00:07:09.629 --> 00:07:12.632
Now let's take a look
at the first tool in this list.

128
00:07:18.871 --> 00:07:22.141
We see that we actually directly
retrieved a set of tools,

129
00:07:22.608 --> 00:07:25.611
and that the first tool
is the summary tool for Meta GPT.

130
00:07:26.312 --> 00:07:29.882
If we take a look at the second tool,
we see that this is a summary tool

131
00:07:29.882 --> 00:07:32.385
for an unrelated paper to Meta GPT and
Swebench,

132
00:07:32.385 --> 00:07:35.855
so, of course, the quality of retrieval
so dependent on your embedding model.

133
00:07:36.456 --> 00:07:39.459
However,
we see that the last tool that's retrieved

134
00:07:39.559 --> 00:07:42.328
is indeed the summary tool for Swebench.

135
00:07:42.328 --> 00:07:45.331
Now we are ready to set up our function
calling agent.

136
00:07:45.565 --> 00:07:49.202
We note that the setup is pretty similar
to the setup in the last lesson.

137
00:07:49.569 --> 00:07:52.939
However, just as an additional feature,
we show that you can actually

138
00:07:52.939 --> 00:07:55.942
add a system prompt to the agent
if you want.

139
00:07:55.942 --> 00:07:56.976
This is optional.

140
00:07:56.976 --> 00:07:59.178
You don't need to specify this,
but you can

141
00:07:59.178 --> 00:08:00.913
if you want, just additional guidance.

142
00:08:00.913 --> 00:08:03.916
If you want to prompt the agent
to output things in a certain way,

143
00:08:04.083 --> 00:08:05.685
if you want it to

144
00:08:05.685 --> 00:08:08.754
take into account certain factors
when it reasons over these tools.

145
00:08:09.522 --> 00:08:11.057
And so this is an example of that.

146
00:08:12.391 --> 00:08:13.693
Now let's try asking

147
00:08:13.693 --> 00:08:16.696
some comparison queries.

148
00:08:17.730 --> 00:08:18.397
We ask:

149
00:08:18.397 --> 00:08:20.099
"Tell me about the eval data set.

150
00:08:20.099 --> 00:08:23.102
Use in Meta GPT
and compare it against Swebench."

151
00:08:34.180 --> 00:08:35.314
We see that it calls

152
00:08:35.314 --> 00:08:39.352
both the summary tool for Meta GPT
as well as the summary tool

153
00:08:39.385 --> 00:08:42.755
for Swebench.
Is able to get back results for both.

154
00:08:44.590 --> 00:08:47.159
And then it generates a final response.

155
00:08:47.159 --> 00:08:50.162
Here.

156
00:08:53.699 --> 00:08:57.803
Now, as a final example, let's compare
and contrast the two Lora papers,

157
00:08:58.037 --> 00:09:02.642
Longlora, as well as LoftQ
and analyze the approach in each paper

158
00:09:02.642 --> 00:09:05.645
first.

159
00:09:08.781 --> 00:09:10.950
We see that
the agent is executing this query,

160
00:09:10.950 --> 00:09:14.220
and the first step it takes
is it takes this input task and actually

161
00:09:14.220 --> 00:09:17.223
retrieves the set of input tools
that help it fulfill this task.

162
00:09:17.623 --> 00:09:21.327
And so through the object retriever,
the hope is that it actually retrieves

163
00:09:21.327 --> 00:09:25.097
longlora and Loftq
query tools in order to help it fulfill

164
00:09:25.097 --> 00:09:28.100
its response.

165
00:09:28.935 --> 00:09:32.939
So if we take a look at the intermediate
outputs of the agent, we see that

166
00:09:32.939 --> 00:09:37.410
it is able to have access to relevant
tools from LongLora and also LoftQ.

167
00:09:38.377 --> 00:09:39.245
We see that first

168
00:09:39.245 --> 00:09:42.281
calls summary tool LongLora
with arguments, approach on LongLora,

169
00:09:42.315 --> 00:09:45.751
and you able to get back
a summary of the approach.

170
00:09:46.552 --> 00:09:50.056
Similarly,
you're able to get back the approach

171
00:09:50.056 --> 00:09:53.059
and LoftQ you by calling summary
tool LoftQ.

172
00:09:54.093 --> 00:09:57.697
The final LLM response
is able to compare these two approaches

173
00:09:57.997 --> 00:10:00.967
by comparing the responses
from these two tools

174
00:10:00.967 --> 00:10:04.503
and combining it to synthesize
an answer that satisfies the user query.

175
00:10:05.137 --> 00:10:07.039
So that concludes our lesson.

176
00:10:07.039 --> 00:10:10.543
So now you should be equipped
with the right tools to build agents

177
00:10:10.543 --> 00:10:13.779
not only over a single document,
but also over multiple documents,

178
00:10:14.246 --> 00:10:17.750
enabling you to build more general,
complex context

179
00:10:17.750 --> 00:10:20.953
augmented research assistance
that can answer complex questions.

